arch:property.oc:show_val: Soil below Locus 1 in the ‘bathroom’ and ‘anteroom’

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Full blockage, robbing out and dumping.

Locus 14 is the soil below Locus 1 in the ‘bathroom’ and ‘anteroom.’ It is a fine but compacted silt with a Munsell of 7.5 YR 4/3 (dark brown). The most noteworthy feature of this locus is the large amount of pottery. Other types of material culture are also present, including bone, stucco, metal, shell, and glass, but none of these compared in quantity to the pottery. This appears to be the result of purposeful dumping in these two rooms, as is also the case for the loci below Locus 14 in each room. Apparently, once the ‘bathroom’ and ‘anteroom’ were no longer functional, they were closed off (the door leading into the ‘anteroom’ was blocked – Locus 25), and filled in. Locus 14 is therefore phased to Stage 5.
4.83 m north south -by- 5.85 m east west.
